meta.text_editor: This demo shows the full capabilities of the Google Routing field. Before using this form you will need to ensure you have entered your Google Maps API key in Settings. Your credentials will require the Directions, Maps and Places API enabled on them. Choose a start and end address and WS Form will make a call to the Directions Service provided by Google Maps JavaScript API to retrieve routing information. The outputs are mapped to various fields on this form. Learn more about the Google Routing field

In this example, Google Address fields are used to determine the start and end addresses. You can also use other field types to allow users to enter an address manually, use a hidden field to specify a fixed start & end address or even use a longitude,latitude string. Learn more about the Google Address field

meta.text_editor: Waypoints are locations the route must pass through between the start and end locations. You can set this section to be a repeater to allow users to add multiple waypoints.

meta.text_editor: When a route is calculated, there are two outcomes. OK - A route has been found ZERO_RESULTS - No route could be determined You can use conditional logic on the Google Routing field to control other form elements based upon these outcomes. Check out the conditional logic on this form. The conditions are only assessed when a route is calculated, therefore we have set the messages below as hidden by default.

In this example, we have assigned the map below in the Google Routing field settings. The route is then shown on the map. You can configure the icons used and the polyline color in the Google Map field settings. Learn more about the Google Map field
